1 Introduction
The study of queueing theory (called also waiting lines) is a quantitative analysis technique.
Waiting lines are an everyday occurrence affecting people buying, shopping, banking, and
waiting in an emergency room… In this part of the course, we discuss how analytical models of
queues can help managers evaluate the cost and effectiveness of a service system.
Examples:
- Supermarkets must decide how many cash register checkout positions should be
opened.
- Gasoline stations must decide how many pumps should be opened and how many
attendants should be on duty.
- Banks must decide how many teller windows to keep open to serve customers during
various hours of the day.
- Manufacturing plants must determine the optimal number of mechanics to have on
duty each shift to repair machines that break down.
2 The Basic Structure of Queueing Models
Figure 1: The basic queueing process.
Figure 1 shows the basic queueing process.
Customers requiring service are generated over time by an input source. These customers enter
the system and join the queue. At certain times, a member of the queue is selected for service
by some rule known as the queue discipline. The required service is then performed for the
customer by the service mechanism, after which the customer leaves the queueing system.
2.1 Input Source
Input source or population is characterized by its size (number of potential customers). It is
either finite or infinite. The assumption is taken that the size is infinite. The statistical pattern
by which customers are generated over time must also be specified.
- Customers are generated according to a Poisson process (the number of customers
generated until any specific time has a Poisson distribution).
ENGG515
Page 3 of 18
- Arrivals to the queueing system occur randomly but at a certain fixed mean rate,
regardless of how many customers already are there.
- The time between consecutive arrivals is referred to as the interarrival time.
- Interarrival time follows the exponential distribution.
2.1.1 Poisson distribution
A Poisson distribution can be used to estimate how likely it is that something will happen “X”
number of times. It is a discrete probability distribution (since arrivals are discrete 0, 1, 2… ).
Customers arrive independently during a certain time interval. The number of arrivals depends
on the length of the time interval.
The formula for the Poisson distribution is:

2.1.2 Exponential distribution
It describes the number of customers serviced in a time interval. The exponential distribution is
a continuous distribution (we can serve partial customer in an interval of time. For example if
we serve 5 in 2 minutes then we can say that we served 2.5 in a minute).

- With an exponential distribution, only the parameter µ is needed to determine the
probability of an event.
- With an exponential distribution, the mean (average) =1/µ and the variance (average
square of the distance from the mean) is 1/µ2.
2.1.2.1 Two key properties of the exponential distribution
1) fT(t) is a strictly decreasing function of t. P{0 ≤ T ≤t} > P{t ≤ T ≤ t +t}
Arrival times sometimes have the appearance of being clustered with occasional large
gaps separating clusters, because of the substantial probability of small interarrival
times and the small probability of large interarrival times, but such an irregular pattern
is all part of true randomness.
2) Lack of memory. P{T>t+t/ T>t} = P{T>t}
The probability distribution of the remaining time until the event (arrival or service
completion) occurs always is the same, regardless of how much time (t) already has
passed. In effect, the process “forgets” its history.
2.2 Queue
The queue is where customers wait before being served.
The queue is characterized as follows:
- Maximum permissible number of customers that it can contain (can be finite or infinite)
- Queue discipline: the order in which members of the queue are selected for service. It
can be:
* first-come-first-served (assumed)
* random
* priority procedure
2.3 Service Mechanism and Service Time
One or more parallel service channels, called servers. The customer enters one of the parallel
service channels and is completely serviced by that server. A queueing model must specify the
number of servers.
Service time:
- The time elapsed from the commencement of service to its completion for a customer
at a server.
- A queueing system must specify the probability distribution of service times for each
server.
- Exponential distribution is used.

Page 6 of 18
3 Elementary Queue
Queueing theory has been applied to many different types of waiting-line situations.
Figure 3: Elementary Queueing system
The elementary queueing system is shown in Figure 3 with one queue and one or more servers.
- The server might be a group of person performing a specific task (repairing a car).
- The customer might not be a person.
The queueing models are indicated as follows:
a / b / c /d with:
a: distribution of interarrival time
b: Distribution of service time
c: Number of servers
d: capacity of the system (waiting and being served)
a and b can be :
- M : exponential distribution
- D: degenerate distribution (constant time)
Examples: M/M/S, M/M/1, M/D/1, M/M/1/N

4 The Birth and Death Process
Most elementary queueing models assume that the inputs (arriving customers) and outputs
(leaving customers) of the queueing system occur according to the birth-and-death process.
Birth: arrival of a new customer into the queueing system.
Death: departure of a served customer.
Assumptions:
1- Given N(t) = n, the current probability distribution of the remaining time until the next
birth (arrival) is exponential with parameter n (n = 0, 1, 2, . . .).
ENGG515
Page 8 of 18
2- Given N(t) = n, the current probability distribution of the remaining time until the next
death (service completion) is exponential with parameter µn (n = 1, 2, . . .).
3- The random variable of assumption 1 (the remaining time until the next birth) and the
random variable of assumption 2 (the remaining time until the next death) are mutually
independent. The next transition in the state of the process is either
n →n+1 (a single birth) or n→ n-1 (a single death) depending on whether the former or
latter random variable is smaller.
Figure 4: state (rate) diagram for the birth and death process
4.1 Analysis of the birth and death process
Exponential distribution implies that n and µn are mean rates. Therefor the arrows in the state
diagram (rate diagram) of Figure 4 show the only possible transitions in the system and the
entry for each arrow gives the mean rate for that transition when the system is in the state at
the base of the arrow.
Consider any particular state of the system n (n = 0, 1, 2. . .). Starting at time 0, suppose that a
count is made of the number of times that the process enters this state and the number of
times it leaves this state, as denoted below:
En(t) = number of times that process enters state n by time t.
Ln(t) = number of times that process leaves state n by time t.
Because the two types of events (entering and leaving since there is no possibility to remain at
the state) must alternate, these two numbers must always either be equal or differ by just 1;
that is, | En(t)- Ln(t)| ≤1 dividing by t and taking the limit when t→ 
We obtain:

4.1.1 Balance equation
Consider state 0, the process enter this state only from state 1. With P1 the probability of being
at state 1, (1-P1) for being at any other state, the total mean rate for entering state 0 is:
µ1P1 + 0(1-P1) = µ1P1 = 0P0. The balance equations for the birth-and-death process are
summarized in the table:

arrival rate is 5 clients every 30 minutes. On the other hand, the average service time (to record
purchases) is 4.5 minutes and this service time is exponentially distributed.
a. What is the average waiting time in the queue at the cash desk for each client?
b. What is the probability that the queue contains at least 3 clients?
c. What is the probability that there are at most 2 clients at the cash desk?
d. What is the average number of clients at the cash desk?

5.2 Model M/M/s
In this model,
- The interarrival time is exponentially distribution (with Poisson as input process)
- The service times are independent and identically distributed according to another
exponential distribution.
- The number of servers is s.
- One waiting queue (see Figure 3)
Going back to the birth and death model, we have
1) µn = nµ when n ≤ s,
2) µn = sµ when n ≥s.
In 1) the number of servers exceeds the number of customers thus some servers are busy and
others are not. The service rate is nµ (all customers are being served)
In 2) the number of servers is less than the number of customers thus some customers are
being served and others are waiting in the queue.
The rate diagram is shown in Figure 6.
ENGG515
Page 13 of 18
Figure 6: rate diagram for M/M/s model
In Figure 6, the more we serve customers at the same time the higher is the service rate.
However, when we reach s (all servers are busy) the service rate become sµ and cannot be
increase. Customers start to wait in the queue.

5.3 Model M/D/1
When the service consists of essentially the same routine task to be performed for all
customers, there tends to be little variation in the service time required. The M/D/s model
often provides a reasonable representation for this kind of situation, because it assumes that all
service times actually equal some fixed constant (the degenerate service-time distribution) and
that we have a Poisson input process with a fixed mean arrival rate .
In this case (without showing the computation of the different statistical measurements) we

5.3.1 First example M/D/1
Drivers who come to get their licenses at the department of motor vehicles have their
photograph taken by an automated machine that develops the photograph onto the license
card and laminates the complete license. The machine requires a constant time of 4.5 minutes
to develop a completed license. If drivers arrive at the machine at the mean rate of 10 per hour
(Poisson distributed), determine the average length of the waiting line and the average waiting
time.

5.3.2 Second example M/D/1
Automata car wash in a one bay facility; cars arrive according to a Poisson distribution with a
mean of 4 cars per hour. Cars may wait in the parking or on the street if the bay is busy. The
service time for washing and cleaning a car is constant and equal to 12 minutes.
a. Determine the model and the rates per hours (arrival and service)
b. Determine the average number of cars in the facility.
c. Determine the average waiting time in the queue.
Solution:
a. The model is M/D/1 =4 cars/hours =60/12 = 5 cars per hour

5.4 Model M/M/1/K
Queue in a queueing system has sometimes a finite length. The number of customers in the
system is not permitted to exceed some specified number (denoted by K) so the queue capacity
is K – 1. Any customer that arrives while the queue is “full” is refused entry into the system and
so leaves forever (an example of such system is an Internet Router with limited memory
capacity). From the viewpoint of the birth-and-death process, the mean input rate into the
system becomes zero at these times.

Determine the following:
a. The steady state probabilities
b. The expected number of customers in the shop.
c. The probability that customers will go elsewhere because the shop is full.
